ingdom":"英國英格蘭薩默塞特","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"英國英格蘭可瓦爾"," England":"英國","lifeSummary":"Robert Smith of Salop是Nn的兒子，於大約1395年出生在英國英格蘭可瓦爾。他於1430年與Lady Alicia Le Brandon在英國結婚。他們至少是1個女兒的父母。他去世於大約1480年在英國英格蘭薩默塞特享年87歲。"},"zh-hans":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"大约1395年–大约1480年","1395–1480":"1395年–1480年","1405–1484":"1405年–1484年","1438–1470":"1438年–1470年","–Male":"殁","Abt 1395":"大约1395年","Abt 1480":"大约1480年","1430":"1430年","1484":"1484年","1395":"1395年","1470":"1470年","1480":"1480年","1438":"1438年","1405":"1405年","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰艾可","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰薩默塞特","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"英国英格兰可瓦爾"," England":"英国","lifeSummary":"Robert Smith of Salop是Nn的儿子，于大约1395年出生在英国英格兰可瓦爾。他于1430年与Lady Alicia Le Brandon在英国结婚。他们至少是1个女儿的父母。他去世于大约1480年在英国英格兰薩默塞特享年87岁。"},"hr":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"oko 1395.–oko 1480.","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438.–1470.","–Male":"preminuo","Abt 1395":"oko 1395.","Abt 1480":"oko 1480.","1430":"1430.","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470.","1480":"1480","1438":"1438.","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engleska, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Engleska, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Engleska, United Kingdom"," England":"England"},"cs":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"okolo 1395–okolo 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Zesnulý","Abt 1395":"okolo 1395","Abt 1480":"okolo 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Anglie, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Anglie, United Kingdom"," England":"Anglie"},"da":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"omkring 1395–omkring 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Afdød","Abt 1395":"omkring 1395","Abt 1480":"omkring 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom"," England":"England"},"nl":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"circa 1395–circa 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Overleden","Abt 1395":"circa 1395","Abt 1480":"circa 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"," England":"England"},"en":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"about 1395–about 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Deceased","Abt 1395":"about 1395","Abt 1480":"about 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom"," England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smithe","meanings":["(1997: 115;2007: 306; 2010: NA)","English: variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smither","meanings":["English (Surrey): occupational name from Middle English <i>smith(i)ere</i>, <i>smeth(i)ere</i> ‘blacksmith’, a derivative of Middle English <i>smithen</i>, <i>smethen</i>, ‘to make (something) in metal, to forge’. Compare   Smith  ."]},{"name":"Smithey","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from Middle English <i>smithi</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old Norse <i>smithja</i>), used either as a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, or an occupational name for someone who worked in one. Compare   Smith   and   Smead  ."]},{"name":"Smyth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ronan, Aidan, Brigid, Conor, Eoin, Malachy, Paddy.","English: variant of   Smith  . This form of the surname is particularly common Ireland."]},{"name":"Smythe","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."]},{"name":"McGowan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Siobhan, Cormac, Seamus, Aileen, Colm, Eithne, Kieran, Niall, Paddy.","Scottish and Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac (a') Ghobhainn</b> or <b>Mac Gobhann</b> (Scottish) or <b>Mac (an) Ghabhann</b> (Irish), ‘son of (the) smith’. This name has also been Anglicized as   Smith   and   Smithson  ."]},{"name":"Smead","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>smeth(e)</i> ‘smith’, a phonetic variant of   Smith   1 that was widespread in medieval England, especially in south-eastern and south-western counties.","topographic, occupational, and habitational name from Middle English <i>smethe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smethe</i>), a side form of   Smith   2, for someone who lived and worked at a blacksmith's, or who lived in or came from a place so named, such as Smeeth (Kent) or Smeed Farm in Hastingleigh (Kent). Compare the synonymous   Smithey  ."]},{"name":"Faber","meanings":["German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), and Danish; Slovak and Czech (mainly <b>Fáber</b>): occupational name from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘blacksmith’. At the time of the Reformation, it was much used as a humanistic name, a translation into Latin of vernacular surnames such as German   Schmidt   and Dutch   Smit  . Compare   Fabri   and   Fauber  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also part of a title. It was François Lefebvre, <i>sieur</i> Duplessis Faber from Paris, France, whose title <i>sieur Duplessis Faber</i> was shortened into the surname <i>Faber</i>. He married Marie-Madeleine Chorel in Champlain, QC, in 1689."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Smith of Salop was born about 1395, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom as the son of Nn. He married Lady Alicia Le Brandon in 1430, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died about 1480, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 87."},"et":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"umbes 1395–umbes 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Surnud","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","Abt 1480":"umbes 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"," England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1395–Abt 1480":"noin 1395–noin 1480","1395–1480":"1395–1480","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1438–1470":"1438–1470","–Male":"Kuollut","Abt 1395":"noin 1395","Abt 1480":"noin 1480","1430":"1430","1484":"1484","1395":"1395","1470":"1470","1480":"1480","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cornwall, England, United Kingdom":"Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"," England":"En